LOCATION:SIDNEY AND LOIS ESKENAZI MUSEUM OF ART
GEO:39.169144;-86.519739
SUMMARY:Eiteljorg Artist In Residence Visiting Lecture: JJ Otero
DESCRIPTION:1–2 p.m. Artist talk\, Learn more about JJ's artistic journ
 ey\, creative philosophy\, and evolving practice\, followed by an open Q+
 A session\, Martin Commons\, second floor2–4 p.m.&#160\;Enjoy hands-on 
 artist programming and a rare look at selected objects from the museum's 
 collections.    JJ Otero (Navajo/Hopi) brings a unique perspective to con
 temporary Native art. After early success as an award-winning musician an
 d later as a painter and cradleboard maker\, he shifted his artistic focu
 s to jewelry and metalsmithing. Since 2018\, his work has been featured a
 t prominent Native art markets\, including the Heard Museum Art Market\, 
 SEEDS Art Market\, and the Santa Fe Indian Market.  Guided by the belief 
 that"This moment is perfect and there's nothing lacking\,"JJ's approach t
 o texture\, stamping\, and form demonstrates both technical rigor and an 
 evolving artistic voice.All of these activities are free and open to the 
 public. This program is co-organized by the IU First Nations Educational 
 and Cultural Center and the Eskenazi Museum of Art\, with support from th
 e Eiteljorg Museum of American Indians and Western Art.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="font-weight: 400\;"><strong>1–2 
 p.m.</strong> Artist talk\, Learn more about JJ's artistic journey\, crea
 tive philosophy\, and evolving practice\, followed by an open Q+A session
 \, Martin Commons\, second floor</p><p style="font-weight: 400\;"><strong
 >2–4 p.m.</strong>&#160\;Enjoy hands-on artist programming and a rare l
 ook at selected objects from the museum's collections.</p><div><p>    JJ 
 Otero (Navajo/Hopi) <span data-contrast="none">brings a unique perspectiv
 e to contemporary Native art. After early success as an award-winning mus
 ician and later as a painter and cradleboard maker\, he shifted his artis
 tic focus to jewelry and metalsmithing. Since 2018\, his work has been fe
 atured at prominent Native art markets\, including the</span> Heard Museu
 m Art Market\, SEEDS Art Market\, and the Santa Fe Indian Market.  </p><p
 ><span data-contrast="none">Guided by the belief that</span><i><span data
 -contrast="none">"This moment is perfect and there's nothing lacking\,"</
 span></i><span data-contrast="none">JJ's approach to texture\, stamping\,
  and form demonstrates both technical rigor and an evolving artistic voic
 e.</span><span data-ccp-props="{&quot\;134233117&quot\;:false\,&quot\;134
 233118&quot\;:false\,&quot\;201341983&quot\;:0\,&quot\;335551550&quot\;:0
 \,&quot\;335551620&quot\;:0\,&quot\;335559738&quot\;:210\,&quot\;33555973
 9&quot\;:210\,&quot\;335559740&quot\;:300}"></span></p><p><span class="Te
 xtRun SCXW242918722 BCX4" lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="no
 ne"><span class="NormalTextRun SCXW242918722 BCX4"><strong>All of these a
 ctivities are free and open to the public. This program is co-organized b
 y the IU First Nations Educational and Cultural Center and the Eskenazi M
 useum of Art\, with support from the Eiteljorg Museum of American Indians
